<sect2><title>Under Windows</title>

<para>
Warning : The Windows version of videolan server can only stream MPEG files stored
on a hard drive. It cannot stream DVDs, satellite channels or real-time
MPEG encoded videos.
</para>

<para>
Download the Zip file for Windows from the <ulink
url="http://www.videolan.org/vls/download.html">videolan server download
page.</ulink>
</para>

<para>
Unzip the file in a directory.
</para>

<sect2><title>Under Linux Debian</title>

<para>
This will only work on Woody or Sid versions, because libdvdread2 is not
present in Potato version.
</para>

<para>
Edit /etc/apt/sources.list and add the following line :
</para>
<para>
<screen><userinput>
	deb http://www.videolan.org/pub/videolan/debian $(ARCH)/
	deb-src http://www.videolan.org/pub/videolan/debian sources/
</userinput></screen>
</para>

<para>
Then type as root :
</para>

<para>
<screen><userinput>
	apt-get update
	apt-get install libdvdcss2 libdvdread2 libdvbpsi1 vls vls-dvd
</userinput></screen>
</para>

<para>
If you don't want to stream DVDs, type instead :
</para>

<para>
<screen><userinput>
	apt-get update
	apt-get install libdvbpsi1 vls
</userinput></screen>
</para>

</sect2>

<sect2><title>Under Linux RedHat, Mandrake or SuSE</title>
<para>
Download the RPM package of libdvdcss from <ulink
url="http://www.videolan.org/pub/videolan/libdvdcss/1.2.2/">
http://www.videolan.org/pub/videolan/libdvdcss/1.2.2/</ulink> and install it.
</para>

<para>
Download the RPM package of libdvbpsi from <ulink url="http://www.videolan.org/libdvbpsi/download.htm">libdvbpsi
download page</ulink> and install it.
</para>

<para>
Download the RPM package of libdvdread from <ulink
url="http://www.dtek.chalmers.se/groups/dvd/redhat.shtm">http://www.dtek.chalmers.se/groups/dvd/redhat.shtml</ulink> and install it.
</para>

<para>
Download the RPM packages vls and vls-dvd from the <ulink url="http://www.videolan.org/vls/download.html">vls download page </ulink>and install them.
</para>

</sect2>

<sect2><title>Under Linux or Unix</title>

<para>
The method below is for any Unix or Linux supported by the videolan
server. We are going
to compile and install the librairies and then the videoaln server.
Install the librairies
</para>

<sect3><title>Install the librairies</title>

<para>
Many librairies are needed for particular uses :
</para>

<itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>Libdvdcss if you want to read encrypted DVDs,</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>Libdvbpsi,</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>Libdvdread if you want to stream DVDs.</para></listitem>
</itemizedlist>

<para>
Download the librairies : take the latest version of libdvdcss from the
<ulink url="http://www.videolan.org/libdvdcss/download.html">libdvdcss download page</ulink>, the latest version of libdvbpsi from the
<ulink url="http://www.videolan.org/libdvbpsi/download.html">libdvbpsi download page</ulink>, and the latest version of libdvdread from
<ulink
url="http://www.dtek.chalmers.se/groups/dvd/downloads.shtml.">http://www.dtek.chalmers.se/groups/dvd/downloads.shtml</ulink>
</para>

<para>
For each librairie, uncompress, configure, compile and install :
</para>

<para>
<screen>
	<prompt>%</prompt><userinput> tar xvzf librairy.tar.gz</userinput>
	<prompt>%</prompt><userinput> cd librairie</userinput>
	<prompt>%</prompt><userinput> ./configure</userinput>
	<prompt>%</prompt><userinput> make</userinput>
	<prompt>%</prompt><userinput> su</userinput>
	<userinput> [enter root password]</userinput>
	<userinput># make install</userinput>
</screen>
</para>

<para>
Check that the configuration file /etc/ld.so.conf contains the line :
</para>

<para>
<screen><userinput>	/usr/local/lib</userinput></screen>
</para>

<para>
If it is not present, as root, add the line and then run ldconfig.
</para>

</sect3>

<sect3><title>Install the videolan server</title>

<para>
Download the sources of the latest release : get the file
vls-version.tar.gz from the vls download page. Uncompress :
</para>

<para>
<screen>
       <prompt>%</prompt><userinput> tar xvzf vls-version.tar.gz</userinput>
       <prompt>%</prompt><userinput> cd vls-version</userinput>
</screen>
</para>

<para>
To get the most recent version of the videolan server, not yet released, you must
use the VideoLAN public CVS:
</para>

<para>
<screen>
	<prompt>%</prompt><userinput> cvs -d:pserver:anonymous@cvs:/cvs/videolan login</userinput>
</screen>
</para>

<para>
There is no password. Type enter, then:
</para>

<para>
<screen>
	<prompt>%</prompt><userinput> cvs -d:pserver:anonymous@cvs:/cvs/videolan checkout -P -r v0_X_X vls</userinput>
</screen>
v0_X_X is the version.
</para>


<para>
To get the list of configuration options, do :
</para>

<para>
<screen>
       <prompt>%</prompt><userinput> ./configure --help</userinput>
</screen>
</para>

<para>
Configure the videolan server. For example :
</para>
<itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>if you want a basic vls without DVD support, do :
</para>

<para>
<screen>
       <prompt>%</prompt><userinput> ./configure --disable-dvd</userinput>
</screen></para></listitem>
<listitem><para>if you want a full videolan server with libdvdcss and DVD support,
you need the libdvdcss librairy,  do :
</para>

<para>
<screen>
       <prompt>%</prompt><userinput> ./configure</userinput>
</screen></para></listitem>
</itemizedlist>
<para>
Then, compile and install :

</para>

<para>
<screen>
	<prompt>%</prompt><userinput> make</userinput>
	<prompt>%</prompt><userinput> su</userinput>
	<userinput> [enter root password]</userinput>
	<userinput># make install</userinput>
</screen>
</para>

<para>
You can also do a make uninstall, make clean or make distclean as
needed.
</para>

</sect3>
</sect2>
